WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.290
to you.

00:00:00.310 --> 00:00:01.140
Great.

00:00:01.140 --> 00:00:02.360
Thank you so much.

00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:05.300
I'm going to wait for people to sit a little bit

00:00:05.300 --> 00:00:05.510
.

00:00:05.510 --> 00:00:06.400
Hi, Skylar.

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:09.170
And if you want to sit in the front, you can

00:00:09.170 --> 00:00:10.760
also sit in the front.

00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:12.520
It is it is safe.

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:14.280
I will not pop quiz you.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:16.480
So wait 30 more seconds.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:19.780
So if you want to get a cup of coffee or something

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:22.240
, you can come through.

00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:25.110
My name is Amber Case.

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:26.830
I go by Case.

00:00:26.830 --> 00:00:30.800
I'm an early blue sky adopter.

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:35.970
And I am trained as a cyborg anthropologist.

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:39.920
So I look at how technology affects culture and how culture affects

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:40.810
technology.

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:44.570
And today I want to get slightly metacognitive and

00:00:44.570 --> 00:00:48.690
think about how do we think about the future as humans?

00:00:48.690 --> 00:00:50.540
And what does that actually mean?

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:52.180
What is the future anyway?

00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:55.190
So I like the idea of local minima.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:57.200
And who knows about local minima in here?

00:00:57.200 --> 00:00:58.420
You can raise your hand.

00:00:58.560 --> 00:00:58.780
Yay.

00:00:58.780 --> 00:00:59.230
Great.

00:00:59.230 --> 00:00:59.880
Good audience.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:04.210
So my non-perfect explanation of local minima is

00:01:04.210 --> 00:01:09.060
you are trying to find either the highest or the lowest point

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:09.900
on a graph.

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:13.450
But sometimes you can get stuck in this local minima.

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:15.520
I don't know if this thing works.

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:18.560
But anyway, so you can see that like little shallow div

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:19.530
ot over there.

00:01:19.530 --> 00:01:21.740
And you can get stuck in the shallow divot.

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:24.020
And because all the other mountains around, you can say,

00:01:24.020 --> 00:01:25.960
well, I'm at the lowest point.

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:27.030
This is great.

00:01:27.060 --> 00:01:29.990
And the only way to get out of that is to walk

00:01:29.990 --> 00:01:30.740
around.

00:01:30.740 --> 00:01:33.270
And you can see the meme about just walk around.

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:33.840
It's fine.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:35.370
But most people might get stuck.

00:01:35.370 --> 00:01:37.550
And they might say, well, I don't even know

00:01:37.550 --> 00:01:38.750
what it is to walk around.

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:42.060
And so in this talk, I want to give you some

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.820
ideas on how to get out of the local minima of

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:47.760
what we think about the future and what we think the future

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:52.260
is and learn how to walk around or different methods of walking

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:55.860
around so that we can reach a different point.

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:59.720
Usually this is someone who says, you know, VR and

00:01:59.730 --> 00:02:00.690
AR are the future.

00:02:00.940 --> 00:02:02.980
Where did they get that idea?

00:02:03.280 --> 00:02:05.080
That's usually a narrative.

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:10.280
And just walking around can be the difference between trying to develop

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:17.180
something for another $80 billion again or, yeah.

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:20.840
So one of my favorite people, I call him the local

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:24.920
big bird of Portland, Oregon, Ward Cunningham.

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:28.340
He's one of my favorite friends, but he created the

00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:28.890
Wiki.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:31.180
But also he has Cunningham's Law.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:34.150
The best way to get the right answer on the internet is

00:02:34.150 --> 00:02:37.220
not to ask a question, but it's to post the

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:38.450
wrong answer.

00:02:38.450 --> 00:02:42.060
But I also love this quote from James Baldwin, which is

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:45.430
, the purpose of art is to lay bare the questions that

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:48.390
have been hidden by the answers.

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:52.150
And I think we have so many things that look like answers

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:57.370
out there that it's incredibly hard to understand what the questions

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:58.090
are.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:01.910
And for most of technology, we can look at once something

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:05.350
gets adopted, it becomes normal, it becomes invisible.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:07.380
We don't question or talk about it.

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:08.200
It just is.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:11.920
We do not have a massive set of headlines that say,

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:15.910
every person at Stanford wants to raise venture capital in order to

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:17.410
make the new light switch.

00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:18.740
It's a light switch.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:22.140
We don't even think about it because it's just normal

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:22.420
.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:24.680
So, so many things in our everyday lives are so normal

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:27.740
because technically they're so well-designed that we don

00:03:27.740 --> 00:03:29.660
't have to think about them anymore.

00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:32.060
And so my question to you, if you can do anything

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:34.940
after this talk, is to look at the things in your

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:38.420
environment that are so well-designed, you no longer

00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:42.360
notice them, and question, where did they come from?

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.360
Who invented them?

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:46.360
Why do they exist?

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:49.620
And then ask different questions, try to come up with,

00:03:49.690 --> 00:03:50.780
with the new questions.

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:53.860
So, there's a lot of false narratives in the way

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.480
of thinking about what the next thing actually is.

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:01.930
And really, innovation comes from the side.

00:04:01.930 --> 00:04:04.280
You might be driving in a car, looking into the front

00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:05.820
, saying, "Oh, what's next?

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:06.460
It's this future.

00:04:06.550 --> 00:04:09.810
It's this future." Or looking behind at what the notion

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:12.780
of the future was told to you was supposed to be the

00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:13.350
future.

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.940
And you might not see it coming.

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:22.730
So, I started to interview people who had been sidesw

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:24.710
iped by the future.

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:28.530
I was interviewing people that worked at Blockbuster.

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:30.310
And they said, "Yay, Blockbuster.

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.620
It was great." And then somebody said, "Well,

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:33.870
we're going to do this new thing.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:35.570
You know, there's, there's, there's,

00:04:35.570 --> 00:04:37.500
of course, Redbox, and then there's Netflix."

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.010
And they said that the majority of people said, "Well

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:42.030
, we're going to work on this thing." And there

00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:43.940
were a few people that said, "We're going to

00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:47.000
digitize content, and load it into the sky, and

00:04:47.080 --> 00:04:50.230
then download it through people's machines." And it wasn't

00:04:50.230 --> 00:04:53.750
until people could clearly see that future, that they could adopt

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:56.350
it, and there was a pathway for them to get to

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:56.740
it.

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:59.000
And there were just a few people on the edge that said

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:00.570
, "Yeah, I can see this future.

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:01.420
It makes sense.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:05.910
This is normal." And then, and then the future sides

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:08.010
wiped a bunch of people.

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:12.980
I was trained at the Institute for the Future, which is

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:17.720
a, at least 50 years of predicting the future.

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:20.200
First, you do not predict one future, you predict multiple

00:05:20.390 --> 00:05:21.130
futures.

00:05:21.130 --> 00:05:24.040
Second, you use the past to understand the future.

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:27.100
And three, you look at cosmotechnics, which is

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.750
the idea that every culture has a technology, not just Silicon

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:33.900
Valley, and that it is 10,000 to a million

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:37.160
years old, and it's site-specific based on the

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:40.230
geography, based on culture, based on history, based on

00:05:40.300 --> 00:05:43.770
food, and that we shouldn't narrow it into technology and

00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:46.310
the future as the last 20 years, but that it is

00:05:46.310 --> 00:05:48.740
all time, and it's extremely sophisticated.

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:51.900
From wind catcher towers in Persia 2,000 years

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:56.170
ago that allowed people to have modern air conditioning and ice cream

00:05:56.170 --> 00:06:00.630
, we can think of everything not as this time right now

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:02.340
, but all time.

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:05.490
And this is the two curves model.

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:09.000
So the first curve is like a signal that masks the future

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:09.230
.

00:06:09.230 --> 00:06:12.360
It's so hard to see the future because the signal is

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:13.370
so weak at first.

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.460
And then the second curve comes up, and it is only

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:21.140
when that first curve declines that that second curve signal gets

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:22.700
strong enough to be seen.

00:06:22.790 --> 00:06:26.060
My dad was an audio engineer, so everything I think about

00:06:26.150 --> 00:06:27.480
is in terms of signal processing.

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:28.100
I'm sorry.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:33.370
Then I started to look at different different types of innovation.

00:06:33.370 --> 00:06:35.270
So Art Frye, who's a banjo player that

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:38.890
worked at 3M, was trying to make the strongest adhesive

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:42.010
in history, and he failed tremendously.

00:06:42.010 --> 00:06:45.100
He made this kind of weak, terrible adhesive that didn't

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:45.520
work.

00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:47.680
And I think his wife at one point was like, "

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:50.830
Hey, I just put these things on the choir notes and

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:54.650
brought them to church, and everybody loves them because you can

00:06:54.650 --> 00:06:57.280
remove them and place them back on." And the sticky note

00:06:57.280 --> 00:06:58.900
was boring, the post-it note.

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:02.620
There's a different side that comes more from constraint.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:06.390
There are a lot of books and interesting history on this,

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:09.960
America's first paramedics, because people didn't have

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:10.740
access.

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:13.220
And it's a really upsetting, tragic story.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:17.060
And then we got this incredible service that people use all the

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:20.420
time now, even though it's been really raised in price

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:22.340
in the United States.

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:27.690
But there's this idea that when there is constraint and discrimination

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:32.170
and non-access, really interesting things can come about

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:34.920
based on the community, based from the ground up.

00:07:34.950 --> 00:07:37.080
It's not a top-down innovation space.

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:39.470
It's not a company saying, "The future is the

00:07:39.470 --> 00:07:42.100
metaverse," and then not understanding anything.

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:45.290
I got to have dinner with this person.

00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:48.020
I spoke at a conference with him, and I saw him

00:07:48.020 --> 00:07:49.630
eating alone, and I was like, "Can I eat

00:07:49.630 --> 00:07:53.700
with you?" And he created - he's a really curious

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:57.510
person, and his mother was one of the hidden figures that

00:07:57.510 --> 00:07:58.260
worked at NASA.

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:02.800
But he tried to figure out how he could get an education

00:08:02.980 --> 00:08:05.360
in a world that didn't support that.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.490
And he ended up working at Bell Labs as an intern,

00:08:08.490 --> 00:08:11.120
and then he had a full-time position at Bell Labs

00:08:11.120 --> 00:08:11.310
.

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:14.860
And he was talking about how not necessarily - if you're

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:18.350
just curious, the microphone that I'm using is using his

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:19.460
technology.

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:22.260
He's a really, really curious person.

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:24.660
But he followed it.

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:30.470
And so a lot of really interesting inventions came forward, not

00:08:30.820 --> 00:08:34.270
because someone was trying to make something, but because they were

00:08:34.270 --> 00:08:37.380
interested in a very small thing and asked an interesting question.

00:08:37.380 --> 00:08:42.840
Also, if anyone knows why, Mario is very small on

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:44.300
the screen.

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:46.360
It was because of a constraint.

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:50.780
So instead of pulling the camera away, which would have required

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:54.600
more memory and processing power, to render a larger portion of

00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:59.380
the screen, the inventor suggested shrinking the size of the character

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:00.140
sprite.

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:03.330
And so the whole game could fit into 32K and about

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:07.000
40K total with the full cartridge data with the code and

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:07.530
graphics.

00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:10.540
Steve Wozniak, the co-founder of Apple

00:09:10.630 --> 00:09:12.830
, was up all night, every night, every night,

00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:14.550
because he really wanted a personal computer.

00:09:14.550 --> 00:09:17.050
And so he's constantly thinking, how could you fit the

00:09:17.060 --> 00:09:20.020
chips onto the motherboard in order to do this?

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:22.470
And he's working at HP at the time.

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:24.770
And of course, the famous thing was, he said,

00:09:24.770 --> 00:09:27.380
"Hey, we invented this small computer." And his boss

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:30.040
said, "No one will want a small desktop computer,

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:32.580
and there's no way it could be that small." And

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:34.340
so Apple was born in the garage.

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:36.500
Also, laziness.

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:39.990
The first webcam was for coffee.

00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:42.610
It was in Cambridge, England.

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:45.060
The idea was, "We don't want to go to

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:48.660
the coffee all the way and see that it was empty,

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:51.380
so we're going to make a webcam." And this was

00:09:51.380 --> 00:09:54.580
the first kind of wormhole to see another space when you

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:55.660
were somewhere else.

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:57.560
And then, of course, it got put on the web

00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:00.340
in 1993 and became an artifact of the web.

00:10:00.410 --> 00:10:04.610
So why are we as humans, not all humans, but

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:10.500
many, many humans, especially in the West and especially in

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:13.370
Silicon Valley, very obsessed with the future?

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:15.260
What is this idea of the future?

00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:17.830
And I use this ostrich thing.

00:10:17.830 --> 00:10:21.380
One part of it was standing on two feet.

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:24.580
When we started to stand on two feet, we had this

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:31.460
huge foundational shift in evolution that was preceding large brain development

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:34.600
, and really acting as a primary driver for neurological and cognitive

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:35.460
advancement.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:40.760
Because you suddenly had your hands free, everything became about using

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:45.170
tools and working with systems over time, and then also increased

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:49.300
efficiency for long-range travel and better thermoregulation

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:50.260
and open landscapes.

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:54.310
But this was a huge neurocomputational shift.

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:57.910
And we also started to look at the horizon, a fixed

00:10:58.030 --> 00:10:58.590
point.

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.980
There are still many cultures that sit down by default.

00:11:02.070 --> 00:11:04.660
I work a lot in Japan, and we sit down when

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:06.010
we think about things.

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.300
And it's a very different way of thinking than standing up

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:12.870
or sitting in an abstracted couch that's extremely, you

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:15.780
know, it's a different way of thinking.

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.820
This is the Chick-Saw tribe.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:21.260
Of course, here's an elder telling a story to a

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:22.100
bunch of kids.

00:11:22.100 --> 00:11:25.470
But I was told by by one of the co-creat

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:31.670
ors of Calm Technology that he was going to explore different ways

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:36.180
of being, and how information got passed down through generations.

00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:38.800
And he was with a First Nations tribe, and he noticed

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:41.620
that all of the kids were not ready to listen.

00:11:41.620 --> 00:11:45.180
And so the elder said, "Go swim across that river

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:47.740
and come back." So all the kids get into the river

00:11:47.880 --> 00:11:49.990
, they swim across the shore, and they come back,

00:11:49.990 --> 00:11:51.550
and they're extremely exhausted.

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:53.590
And then they're sitting down, and they're ready to

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:54.340
listen to a story.

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:58.460
But the most important thing was this is not a PhD level

00:11:58.490 --> 00:11:58.500
.

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:03.810
This is a PhD level of information getting given in a narrative

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:07.230
story that doesn't require a PhD or a research paper to

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:08.100
be published.

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:09.980
It's, you know, how do you tell the pH

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:10.870
of the soil?

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:13.770
Well, we've placed these indicator plants around so you can

00:12:13.770 --> 00:12:15.420
see when this is ready to plant.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:17.640
And now all you have to do is go and observe and

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:19.070
you get this information.

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:22.370
But you tell it in an interesting story because our brains are

00:12:22.370 --> 00:12:25.540
really, really excited about narrative information.

00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:27.490
Extremely excited.

00:12:27.540 --> 00:12:31.040
So excited that, as the first keynote was talking about,

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:33.540
if it's in a nice narrative and you read about it

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:35.940
with enough density that it looks like a thing, that we

00:12:36.010 --> 00:12:38.790
think that we have the knowledge unless we're asked to redo

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:41.540
that or, you know, fix a toilet.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:45.780
But the important part about it is that when it's given

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:48.950
in this structure multi-generationally, you get all sorts

00:12:48.950 --> 00:12:50.500
of interesting information.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:56.060
And sometimes narratives can really go crazy.

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:58.410
